6. Token needs Zone:DNS:Edit permission

=== ROUTE53 SETUP ===
1. Create IAM user in AWS with programmatic access
2. Attach policy: AmazonRoute53FullAccess or custom DNS edit policy
3. Generate Access Key ID and Secret Access Key
4. Enter both in SSLVault DNS provider settings

=== COMMON ERRORS AND FIXES ===

DNS Challenge Failing:
- Ensure DNS provider API key has write (edit) access
- Check TXT record propagation: dig TXT _acme-challenge.yourdomain.com
- Wait 2-5 minutes for DNS propagation before retrying
- Verify correct zone is selected in DNS provider
- Check API key/token permissions

Agent Not Connecting:
- Run: systemctl status sslvault-agent
- Run: journalctl -u sslvault-agent -n 50
- Check internet connectivity from server
- Reinstall agent from /install page
- Verify server credentials are saved correctly in /servers

Certificate Not Renewing:
- Check agent is online in /agent-health
- Verify DNS credentials are saved in /dns-providers
- Check renewal calendar in /renewal-calendar
- Auto-renewal triggers 30 days before expiry
- Manual renewal available in CertVault

KeyLocker Password Forgot:
- KeyLocker password is separate from account password
- Reset not available for security reasons
- Contact support at /contact

TLS Grade Not A+:
- Enable HSTS header (Strict-Transport-Security)
- Disable TLS 1.0 and 1.1 — use only TLS 1.2 and 1.3
- Remove weak cipher suites (RC4, DES, 3DES)
- Enable OCSP Stapling
- Add CAA DNS record
- Use 2048-bit or 4096-bit RSA key, or ECDSA P-256

CAA Record Check:
- SSLVault checks CAA records before issuing
- If CAA restricts to other CAs, issuance will warn
- Add: yourdomain.com CAA 0 issue "trust-anchor.pki.goog" or your CA's domain
- For GoGetSSL: add CAA record for "comodoca.com" or "sectigo.com"

