# Training examples - 300 Q&A pairs
MESSAGE user "What is SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault is a professional SSL/TLS Certificate Lifecycle Management (CLM) platform available at easysecurity.in. It helps businesses discover, monitor, issue, auto-renew, and manage SSL certificates across all their servers and domains. Built by a Certified PKI Specialist, it includes features like CertVault, KeyLocker, auto-renewal agents, DNS provider integrations, and a full PKI intelligence hub."

MESSAGE user "How do I get started with SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Getting started is easy: 1) Visit easysecurity.in and sign up (invite-based). 2) Go to /install and run the one-line agent install command on your VPS. 3) Add your DNS provider credentials at /dns-providers. 4) Go to /buy to issue your first SSL certificate. The agent will automatically handle DNS challenges, certificate installation, and future renewals."

MESSAGE user "How does auto-renewal work?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault auto-renewal works via a persistent bash agent installed on your VPS. The agent polls SSLVault every 5 minutes, checks certificate expiry, and automatically renews certificates 30 days before they expire. It handles the full process: DNS challenge via your configured DNS provider, certificate issuance through GoGetSSL, and installation on your server — all without manual intervention."

MESSAGE user "How do I install the SSLVault agent?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /install on SSLVault. You'll find a one-line bash command — copy and run it on your VPS as root. The agent installs as a systemd service. After installation, verify it's running with: systemctl status sslvault-agent. The agent will appear in your /agent-health dashboard within a few minutes."

MESSAGE user "My agent is not connecting. What should I do?"
MESSAGE assistant "Try these steps: 1) Check status: systemctl status sslvault-agent. 2) View logs: journalctl -u sslvault-agent -n 50. 3) Verify internet connectivity from your server. 4) Check your server credentials are saved correctly in /servers. 5) Try reinstalling the agent from /install. If the issue persists, contact support at /contact."

MESSAGE user "My DNS challenge is failing. How do I fix it?"
MESSAGE assistant "DNS challenge failures are usually caused by: 1) API key/token missing write/edit permission — verify in your DNS provider dashboard. 2) Wrong zone selected — ensure the correct domain zone is selected. 3) DNS propagation delay — wait 2-5 minutes and retry. 4) To manually verify: run dig TXT _acme-challenge.yourdomain.com and check if the TXT record appears. Reconfigure your DNS provider at /dns-providers."

MESSAGE user "What is KeyLocker?"
MESSAGE assistant "KeyLocker is SSLVault's encrypted private key storage system. It securely stores your SSL private keys with: password-protected access (separate from your account password), a 30-second auto-hide timer after revealing, full audit logging of every access event, and copy-only functionality. Access KeyLocker at /keylocker."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Cloudflare DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "To set up Cloudflare: 1) Go to Cloudflare dashboard → My Profile → API Tokens. 2) Click Create Token → use 'Edit zone DNS' template. 3) Set Zone Resources to your specific domain. 4) Copy the generated token. 5) In SSLVault, go to /dns-providers, select Cloudflare, and paste the token. Important: use API Token, NOT the Global API Key."

MESSAGE user "What SSL certificate types does SSLVault support?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault supports three types through GoGetSSL: DV (Domain Validated) — fastest, automated DNS validation, issued in minutes, validates domain ownership only. OV (Organization Validated) — validates organization identity, takes 1-3 days. EV (Extended Validation) — highest trust level, green bar in browsers, most thorough validation. Issue certificates at /buy."

MESSAGE user "How do I check my SSL health score?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /ssl-health-score on SSLVault. Enter your domain and get a grade from A+ to F based on: TLS protocol versions (TLS 1.2/1.3 only = better score), cipher suite strength, HSTS header presence, OCSP stapling, certificate key size, and CAA record presence. The page gives specific recommendations to improve your score."

MESSAGE user "What is the Renewal Calendar?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Renewal Calendar at /renewal-calendar shows a visual month-by-month calendar of all your upcoming certificate renewals. It helps you plan ahead, spot certificates expiring soon, and verify auto-renewal is scheduled correctly. Color-coded entries show renewal urgency — red for urgent, yellow for upcoming, green for safe."

MESSAGE user "How do I add a new server to SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /servers in SSLVault. Click 'Add Server' and enter your server's hostname/IP, SSH credentials (username and password or key), and optional labels. Once added, install the SSLVault agent on that server from /install. The server will then appear in your dashboard with real-time SSL and agent status."

MESSAGE user "What DNS providers does SSLVault support?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault supports 50+ DNS providers including: Cloudflare, AWS Route53, Namecheap, GoDaddy, Porkbun, Dynadot, Name.com, DNSimple, Hover, Gandi, Vultr DNS, DigitalOcean DNS, Linode DNS, Hetzner DNS, and many more. See the full list at /dns-providers with setup guides for each provider."

MESSAGE user "How do I view my certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /certvault to see your complete certificate inventory. You can view certificate details including: domain name, expiry date, issuer, SANs (Subject Alternative Names), trust chain, installation status, and renewal history. Click any certificate for full details including the PEM, chain, and private key (via KeyLocker)."

MESSAGE user "What is the SSL Bulk Scanner?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Bulk Scanner at /scan lets you scan hundreds of domains at once. Enter a list of domains and SSLVault checks each one for: certificate validity, expiry date, issuer, TLS grade, and any issues. Great for auditing all your domains or monitoring competitor/client certificate status."

MESSAGE user "What is a CAA record and why does it matter?"
MESSAGE assistant "A CAA (Certification Authority Authorization) DNS record specifies which Certificate Authorities are allowed to issue certificates for your domain. SSLVault checks CAA records before issuing. If your CAA record restricts issuance to other CAs, you'll get a warning. For GoGetSSL (SSLVault's CA partner), add: yourdomain.com CAA 0 issue 'comodoca.com'. Check your CAA records at /caa-check."

MESSAGE user "What is the Trust Passport?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Trust Passport at /trust-passport is a visual certificate trust chain explorer. Enter any domain and see the complete certificate chain from your domain certificate up through intermediate CAs to the root CA. It helps you verify your chain is complete and correctly configured — a broken chain causes browser warnings."

MESSAGE user "How do I get an A+ TLS grade?"
MESSAGE assistant "To achieve A+ grade: 1) Use only TLS 1.2 and 1.3 (disable TLS 1.0 and 1.1). 2) Remove weak cipher suites (RC4, DES, 3DES, export ciphers). 3) Enable HSTS with max-age of at least 31536000. 4) Enable OCSP Stapling on your web server. 5) Use 2048-bit+ RSA or ECDSA P-256 key. 6) Add a CAA DNS record. Check your current grade at /ssl-health-score."

MESSAGE user "What is the Readiness Dashboard?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Readiness Dashboard at /readiness is a pre-issuance checklist that verifies everything is ready before you request a certificate. It checks: DNS is configured correctly, CAA records allow your CA, domain is reachable, DNS provider credentials are valid, and the agent is connected. Green on all checks means you're ready to issue."

MESSAGE user "How do I contact SSLVault support?"
MESSAGE assistant "Contact SSLVault support at /contact. You can submit a support ticket with your issue details. The AI agent VaultBrain (me) is available 24/7 for instant answers. For complex issues that require account access, the human support team responds via email. Paid plan users get priority support."

MESSAGE user "What is CT Monitor?"
MESSAGE assistant "The CT Monitor at /ct-monitor watches Certificate Transparency logs for your domains. It alerts you when any new certificate is issued for your domain — including by unauthorized parties. This helps detect certificate abuse, mis-issuance, or unauthorized certificate requests for your domains."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up AWS Route53 in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Route53: 1) Log into AWS Console → IAM → Users → Create User with programmatic access. 2) Attach policy: AmazonRoute53FullAccess or a custom policy with route53:ChangeResourceRecordSets permission. 3) Generate Access Key ID and Secret Access Key. 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Route53 and enter both keys. 5) Specify your hosted zone ID."

MESSAGE user "Can I use SSLVault with shared hosting?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, SSLVault has a Shared Hosting Guide at /shared-hosting-guide. For shared hosting where you can't install the agent, SSLVault supports manual DNS validation — you add the TXT record manually in your DNS provider, then SSLVault issues the certificate which you download and install via your hosting control panel (cPanel, Plesk, etc.)."

MESSAGE user "What is the Certificate Changelog?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Certificate Changelog at /cert-changelog shows a complete history of all certificate events: issuances, renewals, reissuances, expirations, and revocations. Each entry shows the timestamp, domain, action taken, and who triggered it. Useful for auditing and compliance reporting."

MESSAGE user "How do I reissue a certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /certvault, find your certificate, and click 'Reissue'. This generates a new certificate with a new key pair while keeping the same domain and settings. Common reasons to reissue: private key compromise, adding/removing SANs, changing key type or size. The agent automatically installs the reissued certificate on your server."

MESSAGE user "What is the Infrastructure page?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Infrastructure page at /infrastructure shows an overview of all your servers and their SSL status in one view. See which servers have valid certificates, which are expiring soon, agent connection status, and overall SSL health across your entire infrastructure at a glance."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up GoDaddy DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For GoDaddy: 1) Log into your GoDaddy account → API Keys (developer.godaddy.com). 2) Create a new API key — note the Key and Secret. 3) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select GoDaddy and enter your API Key and Secret. 4) SSLVault will automatically create and remove DNS TXT records during certificate validation."

MESSAGE user "What happens when a certificate expires?"
MESSAGE assistant "If auto-renewal is properly configured (agent running + DNS credentials saved), SSLVault automatically renews 30 days before expiry — you won't see any downtime. If auto-renewal fails, you'll receive email alerts. You can also manually renew from /certvault at any time. Check /renewal-calendar to see all upcoming expirations."

MESSAGE user "How do I revoke a certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /certvault, select the certificate, and click 'Revoke'. You'll be asked to confirm and select a revocation reason (key compromise, superseded, etc.). Once revoked, the certificate is reported to the CA's CRL (Certificate Revocation List) and OCSP responder. Revocation is permanent — you'll need to issue a new certificate."

MESSAGE user "What is OCSP Stapling?"
MESSAGE assistant "OCSP Stapling is a TLS extension where your web server proactively fetches and caches the OCSP response (certificate validity status) from the CA, then 'staples' it to the TLS handshake. This improves performance (no client OCSP lookup needed) and privacy. Enable it in your web server config: For Nginx: ssl_stapling on; ssl_stapling_verify on; For Apache: SSLUseStapling on."

MESSAGE user "What is HSTS?"
MESSAGE assistant "HSTS (HTTP Strict Transport Security) is a security header that tells browsers to always use HTTPS for your domain, even if users type http://. Add this header to your web server: Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload. The max-age is in seconds (31536000 = 1 year). This is required for an A+ TLS grade."

MESSAGE user "How do I check if my certificate chain is complete?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use SSLVault's Trust Passport at /trust-passport — enter your domain to see the complete chain visually. You can also run: openssl s_client -connect yourdomain.com:443 -showcerts. A complete chain should show: your cert → intermediate CA → root CA. Missing intermediates cause browser warnings. If your chain is incomplete, re-download the full chain bundle from /certvault."

MESSAGE user "What is a wildcard certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "A wildcard certificate covers a domain and all its subdomains — for example *.easysecurity.in covers app.easysecurity.in, api.easysecurity.in, mail.easysecurity.in, etc. SSLVault supports wildcard certificates via DNS validation (HTTP validation cannot verify wildcards). Issue one at /buy by entering *.yourdomain.com as the domain."

MESSAGE user "Can SSLVault monitor certificates I didn't issue through it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes! SSLVault's SSL Discovery feature can find and monitor any certificate, even ones issued elsewhere. Go to /dashboard and use SSL Discovery via CT Logs (searches certificate transparency logs), DNS Scan (scans your DNS records), or Connect to Server (directly checks your server). Discovered certificates are added to /certvault for monitoring."

MESSAGE user "What is a SAN certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "A SAN (Subject Alternative Names) certificate covers multiple domains in a single certificate. For example, one certificate can cover easysecurity.in, www.easysecurity.in, api.easysecurity.in, and app.easysecurity.in. When issuing at /buy, you can add multiple SANs. This is more efficient than separate certificates for each subdomain."

MESSAGE user "How do I add a user to my SSLVault account?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault uses an invite-based system. As master_admin, go to your account settings and send an invitation email. The invitee receives a magic link, clicks it, and sets their password. They're added as an end_customer with access to manage their own certificates and servers. Contact support at /contact for enterprise multi-user setup."

MESSAGE user "What is PKI?"
MESSAGE assistant "PKI (Public Key Infrastructure) is the framework of policies, procedures, hardware, software, and digital certificates that enables secure electronic communications. It uses asymmetric cryptography — a public key (shared openly) and private key (kept secret) — to encrypt data, verify identities, and create digital signatures. SSL/TLS certificates are the most common PKI application."

MESSAGE user "What is the difference between DV, OV, and EV certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "DV (Domain Validated): Verifies only domain ownership. Fastest (minutes), cheapest, good for most websites. Shows padlock in browser. OV (Organization Validated): Verifies domain + organization identity. Takes 1-3 days, requires business documents. Better for business sites. EV (Extended Validation): Most thorough — verifies domain, organization, legal existence, physical address. Highest trust, used by banks and major enterprises. All three encrypt traffic equally — the difference is in identity verification level."

MESSAGE user "How does DNS validation work?"
MESSAGE assistant "DNS validation proves you own a domain by having you add a specific TXT record. SSLVault's process: 1) You request a certificate. 2) SSLVault generates a unique TXT record value. 3) The agent automatically adds this TXT record to your DNS (via your DNS provider API). 4) The CA (GoGetSSL) checks for the TXT record. 5) Once verified, the certificate is issued. 6) The agent removes the TXT record. The whole process takes 2-5 minutes when automated."

MESSAGE user "What port does SSL/TLS use?"
MESSAGE assistant "Standard ports: HTTPS (SSL/TLS): port 443. HTTP (unencrypted): port 80. SMTP with TLS: port 587 (STARTTLS) or 465 (SMTPS). IMAP with TLS: port 993. POP3 with TLS: port 995. FTP with TLS: port 990. SSLVault monitors port 443 by default but can be configured to monitor custom ports for your services."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate pinning?"
MESSAGE assistant "Certificate pinning is a security technique where an application 'pins' (hardcodes) a specific certificate or public key, rejecting any other certificate even if it's valid. Used in mobile apps for extra security. However, it's risky — if the pinned certificate expires and isn't updated in the app, the app breaks. Not recommended for most web applications."

MESSAGE user "How do I enable HTTPS redirect?"
MESSAGE assistant "To redirect HTTP to HTTPS: Nginx: Add 'return 301 https://$host$request_uri;' in your port 80 server block. Apache: Add 'RewriteRule ^(.*)$ https://%{HTTP_HOST}$1 [R=301,L]' in .htaccess or VirtualHost. Cloudflare: Enable 'Always Use HTTPS' in SSL/TLS settings. After setting up the redirect, test with: curl -I http://yourdomain.com"

MESSAGE user "What is ACME protocol?"
MESSAGE assistant "ACME (Automated Certificate Management Environment) is a protocol that automates certificate issuance and renewal between web servers and Certificate Authorities. Let's Encrypt popularized it. SSLVault's agent uses ACME-compatible flows with GoGetSSL to automate the full certificate lifecycle — no manual steps needed once configured."

MESSAGE user "How long does certificate issuance take?"
MESSAGE assistant "DV certificates via SSLVault typically issue in 2-5 minutes when using automated DNS validation. The process: submit request (seconds) → DNS TXT record created by agent (seconds) → CA validates TXT record (1-2 minutes) → certificate issued and installed (seconds). OV and EV certificates require manual CA review and can take 1-5 business days."

MESSAGE user "What is OCSP?"
MESSAGE assistant "OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) allows browsers to check if a certificate has been revoked in real-time. When you visit a site, your browser contacts the CA's OCSP responder to verify the certificate is still valid. This is more efficient than downloading the full CRL (Certificate Revocation List). Enable OCSP Stapling on your server to cache this response locally and improve performance."

MESSAGE user "Can I export my certificates from SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes. Go to /certvault, select your certificate, and you can download: the certificate PEM file, the full certificate chain (certificate + intermediates), the private key (from KeyLocker, requires password), PKCS#12 (.p12) bundle for some applications. Store downloaded private keys securely — they grant full control over the certificate."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate transparency?"
MESSAGE assistant "Certificate Transparency (CT) is a public log system where all issued SSL certificates are recorded. Every CA must log certificates to public CT logs. This allows anyone to monitor for unauthorized certificate issuance. SSLVault's CT Monitor (/ct-monitor) watches these logs for your domains and alerts you to any new certificates — helping detect certificate abuse."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up email alerts for expiring certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault sends automatic email alerts before certificate expiry. Configure alert thresholds in your account settings — typically set to 30 days, 14 days, and 7 days before expiry. Ensure your account email is verified. With a properly configured agent and DNS credentials, certificates will auto-renew before these alerts trigger."

MESSAGE user "What is a CSR?"
MESSAGE assistant "A CSR (Certificate Signing Request) is a block of encoded text containing your public key and domain information, submitted to a CA to request a certificate. SSLVault generates CSRs automatically when you request a certificate at /buy — you don't need to create one manually. If you need a custom CSR (for OV/EV with specific organization details), you can generate one and submit it."

MESSAGE user "How do I check if my certificate is properly installed?"
MESSAGE assistant "Several ways to verify: 1) Use SSLVault's SSL Health Score at /ssl-health-score. 2) Visit your site in a browser and click the padlock icon. 3) Run: openssl s_client -connect yourdomain.com:443. 4) Use online tools like SSL Labs (ssllabs.com/ssltest). Common issues: incomplete chain (missing intermediate), wrong certificate for domain, certificate not yet propagated."

MESSAGE user "What is the difference between SSL and TLS?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) is the older protocol — SSL 2.0 and 3.0 are both deprecated and insecure. TLS (Transport Layer Security) is the modern replacement — TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are deprecated, TLS 1.2 and 1.3 are current standards. Despite this, the industry still commonly says 'SSL certificate' when technically meaning TLS certificates. SSLVault configures TLS 1.2 and 1.3 by default."

MESSAGE user "What is a root certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "A root certificate is the top-level certificate in a trust chain, issued by a Root Certificate Authority (Root CA). Root CAs are trusted organizations whose certificates are pre-installed in operating systems and browsers (the 'root store'). Intermediate CAs issue your domain certificates, chaining back to the root. This chain structure allows the CA system to scale while keeping root keys offline and secure."

MESSAGE user "How do I add multiple domains to one certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "When issuing at /buy, add your primary domain and then list additional SANs (Subject Alternative Names). For example: primary domain: easysecurity.in, SANs: www.easysecurity.in, api.easysecurity.in, app.easysecurity.in. Each SAN requires DNS validation. You can have dozens of SANs on one certificate — more efficient than separate certificates."

MESSAGE user "What is forward secrecy?"
MESSAGE assistant "Forward Secrecy (also called Perfect Forward Secrecy or PFS) ensures that even if a server's private key is compromised in the future, past encrypted sessions cannot be decrypted. It works by generating unique session keys for each connection that are discarded after use. Enable it by using ECDHE or DHE cipher suites. SSLVault's health score checks for forward secrecy support."

MESSAGE user "How do I renew a certificate manually?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to /certvault, find the certificate you want to renew, and click 'Renew'. SSLVault will: generate a new certificate request, perform DNS validation via the agent, issue a new certificate from GoGetSSL, and install it on your server. Manual renewal is instant if your agent is online and DNS credentials are configured. You can renew at any time, not just when near expiry."

MESSAGE user "What happens if my server is offline during auto-renewal?"
MESSAGE assistant "If the server is offline when renewal is attempted: the agent can't complete the DNS challenge or certificate installation. SSLVault will retry on the next agent poll (every 5 minutes). Email alerts will notify you of the failed renewal. Once the server comes back online, the agent will attempt renewal again. If the certificate expires due to prolonged downtime, manual intervention is needed."

MESSAGE user "What is a PEM file?"
MESSAGE assistant "PEM (Privacy Enhanced Mail) is the most common certificate format — a Base64-encoded file starting with -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE----- and ending with -----END CERTIFICATE-----. Your certificate, intermediate chain, and private key can all be in PEM format. SSLVault downloads certificates in PEM format. Nginx and Apache use PEM files directly."

MESSAGE user "What is a PKCS#12 file?"
MESSAGE assistant "PKCS#12 (.p12 or .pfx) is a binary certificate format that bundles the certificate, full chain, and private key in one encrypted file. Used by Windows servers (IIS), Java applications, and some load balancers. Download PKCS#12 from SSLVault's /certvault. You'll need to set a password to protect the bundle."

MESSAGE user "How do I install a certificate on Nginx?"
MESSAGE assistant "1) Download your certificate and chain from SSLVault /certvault. 2) Upload to your server (e.g., /etc/nginx/ssl/). 3) In your Nginx config: ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/yourdomain.crt; ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/yourdomain.key; ssl_trusted_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/chain.crt; 4) Test: nginx -t 5) Reload: systemctl reload nginx. SSLVault's agent handles this automatically if properly configured."

MESSAGE user "How do I install a certificate on Apache?"
MESSAGE assistant "1) Download certificate files from SSLVault /certvault. 2) Upload to your server. 3) In Apache VirtualHost: SSLEngine on; SSLCertificateFile /etc/ssl/yourdomain.crt; SSLCertificateKeyFile /etc/ssl/yourdomain.key; SSLCertificateChainFile /etc/ssl/chain.crt; 4) Test: apachectl configtest 5) Restart: systemctl restart apache2. SSLVault's agent can handle this automatically."

MESSAGE user "What is the SSLVault agent daemon?"
MESSAGE assistant "The SSLVault agent daemon is a persistent bash service that runs on your Linux VPS. It polls SSLVault's servers every 5 minutes to: check for pending certificate jobs, perform DNS challenges using your configured DNS provider, install newly issued certificates, monitor certificate expiry, and report server and certificate health back to your dashboard."

MESSAGE user "How do I check agent logs?"
MESSAGE assistant "View agent logs with: journalctl -u sslvault-agent -n 100 (last 100 lines) or journalctl -u sslvault-agent -f (follow live logs) or journalctl -u sslvault-agent --since '1 hour ago'. Look for error messages about DNS failures, connection timeouts, or certificate installation issues. Share relevant logs when contacting support at /contact."

MESSAGE user "What Linux distributions does the SSLVault agent support?"
MESSAGE assistant "The SSLVault agent supports major Linux distributions including: Ubuntu 18.04, 20.04, 22.04, 24.04, Debian 10, 11, 12, CentOS 7, 8, Rocky Linux 8, 9, AlmaLinux 8, 9, and other systemd-based Linux distributions. The agent requires bash, curl, and systemd. Minimum requirements: 512MB RAM, 1GB disk space."

MESSAGE user "Does SSLVault support IPv6?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, SSLVault supports IPv6. Your server can have both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses. Certificate issuance validates via DNS (not HTTP), so IPv6-only servers are fully supported. SSL monitoring works for both IPv4 and IPv6 endpoints. Configure your server's IPv6 address in /servers."

MESSAGE user "What is the Developer API?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault provides a REST API documented at /developer. The API allows you to: list and manage certificates programmatically, trigger certificate issuance and renewal, check agent status, manage DNS providers, and integrate SSLVault into your own systems or CI/CD pipelines. Authentication uses API keys generated in your account settings."

MESSAGE user "How secure is SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault is built with security-first design: private keys are encrypted at rest, KeyLocker requires a separate password for key access, all key reveals are logged in the audit trail, keys auto-hide after 30 seconds, the platform uses HTTPS exclusively, role-based access control limits what each user can see and do, and the invite-only system prevents unauthorized registration."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate pinning and should I use it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Certificate pinning hardcodes a specific certificate or public key in your application, rejecting all others. While it adds security against MITM attacks, it's generally NOT recommended for web applications because: certificate renewal will break pinned apps unless you update them simultaneously, it adds significant operational complexity, and modern TLS with proper CA validation is sufficient for most use cases. Only consider it for high-security mobile apps."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Namecheap DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Namecheap: 1) Log into Namecheap → Profile → Tools → API Access. 2) Enable API access and whitelist your SSLVault server IP. 3) Note your API Key and username. 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Namecheap and enter your username and API key. 5) Ensure your account has API access enabled (requires minimum account balance on Namecheap)."

MESSAGE user "Can I use SSLVault for internal/intranet certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "Public SSL certificates require publicly accessible domains (publicly resolvable DNS). For internal/intranet use: if your internal domain is publicly resolvable (e.g., internal.company.com), SSLVault can issue certificates for it. For private domains (.local, .internal, private IPs), public CAs cannot issue certificates — you'd need a private CA. Contact support at /contact for enterprise private CA solutions."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate transparency and how does it affect me?"
MESSAGE assistant "Certificate Transparency (CT) requires all publicly trusted CAs to log every certificate they issue to public CT logs. This means: any certificate issued for your domain is publicly visible in CT logs. SSLVault's CT Monitor (/ct-monitor) watches these logs and alerts you to new certificates for your domains. This is a benefit — it helps you detect unauthorized certificate issuance for your domains."

MESSAGE user "How do I migrate from Let's Encrypt to SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Migration is simple: 1) Add your server to SSLVault at /servers. 2) Install the SSLVault agent. 3) Configure your DNS provider at /dns-providers. 4) Issue a new certificate for your domain at /buy. 5) The agent will install the new certificate and configure auto-renewal. 6) You can let the Let's Encrypt certificate expire naturally, or stop the certbot service to prevent conflicts."

MESSAGE user "Does SSLVault work with Cloudflare proxied domains?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, with a caveat. For DNS validation (which SSLVault uses), Cloudflare proxying doesn't affect the process — SSLVault adds a TXT record for _acme-challenge which is not proxied. However, if you're using Cloudflare's SSL (Full or Full Strict mode), be aware that Cloudflare terminates SSL at their edge. Your origin certificate (issued by SSLVault) only encrypts traffic between Cloudflare and your server."

MESSAGE user "What is the difference between SSL termination and SSL passthrough?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSL Termination: The load balancer/proxy decrypts SSL traffic, communicates with your backend in plain HTTP, then re-encrypts for the response. Easier to manage certificates centrally, but traffic between load balancer and backend is unencrypted internally. SSL Passthrough: Encrypted traffic passes through the proxy without decryption — your backend server handles SSL. More secure end-to-end but harder to do header inspection. SSLVault supports both architectures."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Porkbun DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Porkbun: 1) Log into Porkbun → Account → API Access → Enable API access. 2) Note your API Key and Secret API Key. 3) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Porkbun and enter both keys. 4) Select the domain you want to automate. Porkbun's API is simple and reliable — one of the easiest providers to set up."

MESSAGE user "What is the SSLVault Knowledge Base?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Knowledge Base at /knowledge-base contains detailed help articles covering: agent installation and troubleshooting, DNS provider setup guides for all supported providers, certificate issuance workflows, TLS configuration best practices, common error solutions, and PKI concepts explained clearly. It's searchable and regularly updated."

MESSAGE user "How do I set a custom renewal threshold?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault's default auto-renewal threshold is 30 days before expiry. To customize: go to your account settings or certificate settings in /certvault, find the renewal threshold option, and set your preferred days. You can also set multiple alert thresholds (e.g., alert at 30 days, 14 days, 7 days) to ensure you're always notified before auto-renewal runs."

MESSAGE user "What does 'certificate not trusted' mean?"
MESSAGE assistant "A 'certificate not trusted' error means the browser cannot verify the certificate's authenticity. Common causes: 1) Incomplete certificate chain — missing intermediate CA. Fix: download the full chain from /certvault and configure your server to serve it. 2) Self-signed certificate — not issued by a trusted CA. 3) Certificate installed on wrong domain — check the CN and SANs. 4) Expired certificate — renew immediately."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up DigitalOcean DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For DigitalOcean: 1) Log into DigitalOcean → API → Generate New Token. 2) Give it a name and enable Write scope. 3) Copy the token. 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select DigitalOcean and enter your API token. 5) Make sure your domain's nameservers point to DigitalOcean (ns1.digitalocean.com, ns2.digitalocean.com, ns3.digitalocean.com)."

MESSAGE user "What is DANE and TLSA records?"
MESSAGE assistant "DANE (DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities) uses TLSA DNS records to bind certificates to specific domain names using DNSSEC. A TLSA record specifies which certificate or public key is valid for your domain. It provides an additional layer of certificate validation independent of CAs. SSLVault's CA Intelligence Hub covers DANE best practices. Not widely used yet but growing in enterprise PKI."

MESSAGE user "How do I handle certificate errors in Chrome?"
MESSAGE assistant "Common Chrome SSL errors and fixes: NET::ERR_CERT_AUTHORITY_INVALID — Certificate not trusted, check chain at /trust-passport. NET::ERR_CERT_DATE_INVALID — Certificate expired, renew immediately in /certvault. NET::ERR_CERT_COMMON_NAME_INVALID — Domain mismatch, check SANs in /certvault. NET::ERR_SSL_PROTOCOL_ERROR — TLS handshake failure, check TLS version and ciphers at /ssl-health-score."

MESSAGE user "What is the CA Intelligence Hub?"
MESSAGE assistant "The CA Intelligence Hub at /ca-intelligence aggregates news, updates, and compliance information from major Certificate Authorities including DigiCert, Sectigo, GlobalSign, and others. It also covers CA/Browser Forum decisions, ballot results, and policy changes that affect SSL certificate requirements. Essential reading for PKI professionals and compliance teams."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Hetzner DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Hetzner DNS: 1) Log into Hetzner DNS Console (dns.hetzner.com). 2) Go to your account → API Tokens → Create API Token. 3) Give it a name and create it — note the token value (shown once). 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Hetzner and enter your API token. 5) Ensure your domain is managed in Hetzner DNS."

MESSAGE user "Can I use SSLVault API in CI/CD pipelines?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes! SSLVault's developer API at /developer is designed for CI/CD integration. You can: automatically issue certificates as part of deployment, trigger renewals before deploying new server instances, verify certificate status in health checks, and manage certificates for ephemeral environments. Use the API key from your account settings for authentication."

MESSAGE user "What is an intermediate certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "An intermediate certificate sits between your domain certificate and the root CA certificate in the trust chain. Root CAs use intermediate CAs to sign end-entity certificates, keeping the root key offline and secure. Your server must serve both your certificate AND the intermediate(s) for browsers to build a complete trust chain. SSLVault downloads the complete chain bundle from /certvault."

MESSAGE user "How do I backup my certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "From SSLVault /certvault: download the certificate PEM, the full chain bundle, and the private key (from KeyLocker, requires password). Store backups in a secure, encrypted location. Best practices: encrypt backups with a strong password, store in multiple locations, test restoration periodically, never store unencrypted private keys on shared systems. SSLVault's KeyLocker provides secure in-platform key storage."

MESSAGE user "What is ETSI and why does it matter for PKI?"
MESSAGE assistant "ETSI (European Telecommunications Standards Institute) develops PKI standards widely used in the EU, particularly for qualified certificates and electronic signatures under eIDAS regulation. SSLVault's PKI Hub at /pki-hub/etsi covers ETSI standards. For businesses operating in the EU, ETSI-compliant certificates may be required for electronic signatures, qualified timestamping, and regulatory compliance."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Vultr DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Vultr DNS: 1) Log into Vultr → Account → API → Enable API access. 2) Copy your API Key. 3) Whitelist your server IP if IP restriction is enabled. 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Vultr and enter your API key. 5) Ensure your domain uses Vultr's nameservers (ns1.vultr.com, ns2.vultr.com)."

MESSAGE user "What is eIDAS?"
MESSAGE assistant "eIDAS (Electronic Identification, Authentication and Trust Services) is an EU regulation that establishes standards for electronic identification and trust services across EU member states. It defines requirements for qualified electronic signatures, qualified certificates, and electronic seals. SSLVault's PKI Hub at /pki-hub/eidas covers eIDAS compliance requirements for businesses needing legally binding electronic signatures in the EU."

MESSAGE user "What is the NIST framework for PKI?"
MESSAGE assistant "NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology) provides PKI guidelines through publications like NIST SP 800-57 (key management) and NIST SP 800-63 (digital identity). These are widely referenced in US federal and regulated industry PKI implementations. SSLVault's PKI Hub at /pki-hub/nist covers relevant NIST guidelines for certificate management and key security."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Linode/Akamai DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Linode (now Akamai Cloud): 1) Log into Linode Cloud Manager → Profile → API Tokens → Add Personal Access Token. 2) Set Read/Write access for Domains. 3) Copy the token. 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Linode and enter your API token. 5) Ensure your domain's nameservers point to Linode DNS (ns1.linode.com through ns5.linode.com)."

MESSAGE user "What is a multi-domain certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "A multi-domain certificate (also called UCC — Unified Communications Certificate) covers multiple different domains in one certificate using SANs. Example: one certificate for easysecurity.in, api.easysecurity.in, app.easysecurity.io, and mycustomdomain.com. Unlike wildcard certificates which cover all subdomains of one domain, multi-domain certs can cover completely different domain names. Issue at /buy by listing all domains."

MESSAGE user "What is IETF's role in TLS?"
MESSAGE assistant "The IETF (Internet Engineering Task Force) defines TLS protocol standards through RFCs. Key TLS RFCs: RFC 8446 (TLS 1.3), RFC 5246 (TLS 1.2). The IETF's TLS working group continues to develop security improvements. SSLVault follows IETF standards — only TLS 1.2 and 1.3 are supported; older versions are deprecated per IETF recommendations. See /pki-hub/ietf for current IETF TLS developments."

MESSAGE user "How does SSLVault handle private key security?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault's key security model: private keys are encrypted at rest in the database, KeyLocker requires a separate password to reveal any key, revealed keys are shown for maximum 30 seconds then hidden, all key access is logged in the audit trail, copy-only interface prevents key display in screenshots, and keys cannot be exported without KeyLocker password. This multi-layer approach ensures keys are protected even if the database is compromised."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate stapling?"
MESSAGE assistant "Certificate stapling (OCSP Stapling) is when your web server proactively obtains and caches the OCSP response for your certificate, then includes it in the TLS handshake. This prevents browsers from needing to contact the CA's OCSP server during every connection — improving performance and privacy. Configure in Nginx: ssl_stapling on; ssl_stapling_verify on; resolver 8.8.8.8; In Apache: SSLUseStapling On;"

MESSAGE user "What is the CA/Browser Forum?"
MESSAGE assistant "The CA/Browser Forum (CABF) is an industry group of Certificate Authorities and browser vendors that sets baseline requirements for publicly trusted SSL certificates. Their decisions directly affect what certificates CAs can issue. SSLVault's CA Intelligence Hub at /cab-forum covers all CA/Browser Forum ballot results, policy changes, and compliance requirements. All certificates issued through SSLVault comply with current CABF baseline requirements."

MESSAGE user "How do I know if my certificate will be trusted by all browsers?"
MESSAGE assistant "Certificates issued through SSLVault via GoGetSSL are trusted by all major browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge, Opera) and operating systems (Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, Android) because GoGetSSL chains to widely trusted root CAs. Verify trust at /trust-passport — enter your domain to see the complete chain. You can also check at ssllabs.com for comprehensive browser compatibility testing."

MESSAGE user "What is key rotation and when should I do it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Key rotation means generating a new private key and reissuing the certificate. You should rotate keys: if you suspect the private key was compromised, as part of regular security hygiene (annually recommended), after a team member with key access leaves, when changing key type or size (e.g., from RSA 2048 to ECDSA P-256). In SSLVault, use the 'Reissue' option in /certvault to generate a new key pair and fresh certificate."

MESSAGE user "What is Gandi DNS setup in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Gandi: 1) Log into Gandi → Organization → Security → Personal Access Token. 2) Create a new token with DNS Records Write permission. 3) Copy the token. 4) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Gandi and enter your API token. Gandi uses their LiveDNS API v5. Ensure your domain uses Gandi's nameservers."

MESSAGE user "How do I configure TLS on Nginx for A+ grade?"
MESSAGE assistant "Nginx TLS configuration for A+ grade: ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3; ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305; ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off; add_header Strict-Transport-Security 'max-age=63072000' always; ssl_stapling on; ssl_stapling_verify on; Check your grade at /ssl-health-score."

MESSAGE user "What is ECDSA vs RSA certificate?"
MESSAGE assistant "RSA (Rivest-Shamir-Adleman): Traditional algorithm, widely compatible. Common sizes: 2048-bit (minimum) or 4096-bit. Larger key = more CPU intensive. ECDSA (Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm): Newer algorithm, smaller key size = same security. ECDSA P-256 = equivalent to RSA 3072-bit, but much faster. Better performance, especially on mobile. SSLVault supports both — choose ECDSA P-256 for new certificates when possible."

MESSAGE user "How do I monitor SSL certificates across multiple servers?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault is designed for multi-server monitoring. Install the agent on each server (they all report back to your SSLVault dashboard). View all servers at /servers, all certificates at /certvault, agent status at /agent-health, and a complete infrastructure overview at /infrastructure. The renewal calendar at /renewal-calendar shows expiry dates across all servers in one view."

MESSAGE user "What happens to my data if I cancel SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Your certificate data including PEM files, chain, and metadata remain in SSLVault for a grace period after cancellation. Private keys in KeyLocker are only accessible with your KeyLocker password — export them before cancelling. We recommend downloading all certificates and keys from /certvault before cancelling. Contact support at /contact for data export assistance or migration planning."

MESSAGE user "Does SSLVault support Let's Encrypt certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault's primary CA integration is GoGetSSL for issuing DV, OV, and EV certificates. However, SSLVault can monitor and manage any certificate including those issued by Let's Encrypt — import them via SSL Discovery at /dashboard. The auto-renewal agent works with GoGetSSL-issued certificates. If you're migrating from Let's Encrypt, see the migration guide in /knowledge-base."

MESSAGE user "What is APKIC?"
MESSAGE assistant "APKIC (Asia Pacific PKI Consortium) promotes PKI adoption and standards across the Asia Pacific region. SSLVault's PKI Hub at /pki-hub/apkic covers APKIC guidelines and regional PKI developments. For businesses operating in Asia Pacific with regulatory PKI requirements, APKIC resources are relevant for compliance planning."

MESSAGE user "How do I renew certificates for a domain with CAA restrictions?"
MESSAGE assistant "If your domain has CAA records, ensure they include the CA used by SSLVault (GoGetSSL uses Sectigo/Comodo infrastructure). Add this CAA record: yourdomain.com CAA 0 issue 'comodoca.com' and yourdomain.com CAA 0 issue 'sectigo.com'. Check your current CAA records at /caa-check. If CAA records are missing your CA, renewal will fail with a CAA violation error."

MESSAGE user "Can SSLVault manage certificates for Docker containers?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes. For Docker: 1) Install the SSLVault agent on the host server (not inside containers). 2) Mount certificate directories as Docker volumes. 3) The agent renews certificates and writes them to the mounted path. 4) Trigger container reload via a post-renewal hook (configurable in agent settings). Alternatively, use a reverse proxy like Traefik or Nginx on the host to handle SSL and forward to containers."

MESSAGE user "What is the PKI Consortium?"
MESSAGE assistant "The PKI Consortium (PKIC) is a non-profit organization promoting PKI technologies and best practices globally. They publish research, organize events, and advocate for strong PKI implementations. SSLVault's PKI Hub at /pki-hub/pkic covers PKI Consortium resources and publications. Useful for organizations building enterprise PKI programs."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up DNS.js or name.com in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Name.com: 1) Log into Name.com → Account → API → Enable API access. 2) Note your username and API token. 3) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Name.com and enter your username and API token. Name.com API is straightforward — same credentials as your account but with API token instead of password."

MESSAGE user "What security headers should I add alongside SSL?"
MESSAGE assistant "Alongside HTTPS, add these security headers: 1) HSTS: Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload. 2) CSP: Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'. 3) X-Frame-Options: DENY. 4) X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff. 5) Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin. 6) Permissions-Policy to control browser features. Test all headers at securityheaders.com. SSLVault's Health Score at /ssl-health-score checks HSTS."

MESSAGE user "What is the CSC (Cloud Signature Consortium)?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Cloud Signature Consortium (CSC) defines standards for cloud-based digital signatures, enabling remote signing of documents using certificates stored in the cloud. SSLVault's PKI Hub at /pki-hub/csc covers CSC standards. Relevant for organizations implementing cloud-based document signing solutions."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up DNSimple in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For DNSimple: 1) Log into DNSimple → Account → API Access Tokens → Add Access Token. 2) Name it and create — copy the token (shown once). 3) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select DNSimple and enter your account ID and API token. Your account ID is found in your DNSimple account settings. DNSimple has a clean API that works reliably for automation."

MESSAGE user "How does SSLVault handle certificate revocation?"
MESSAGE assistant "When you revoke a certificate in SSLVault via /certvault → Revoke: SSLVault sends a revocation request to GoGetSSL, the CA updates its CRL (Certificate Revocation List), the OCSP responder immediately marks the certificate as revoked, browsers checking OCSP will see it as revoked within minutes, CRL updates may take up to 24 hours to propagate fully. Always issue a replacement certificate before or immediately after revoking."

MESSAGE user "What browsers does SSLVault support?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault (easysecurity.in) works on all modern browsers: Chrome 90+, Firefox 88+, Safari 14+, Edge 90+, and Opera 76+. The dashboard is responsive and works on mobile browsers too. Certificates issued through SSLVault are trusted by all these browsers plus their mobile versions. The SSLVault agent runs on Linux servers regardless of what browser you use to access the dashboard."

MESSAGE user "How do I verify a certificate's signature?"
MESSAGE assistant "Verify a certificate's chain of trust with: openssl verify -CAfile chain.pem certificate.pem. Or check online using SSLVault's Trust Passport at /trust-passport. You can also view certificate details with: openssl x509 -in certificate.pem -text -noout. This shows the issuer, subject, SANs, validity dates, public key info, and signature algorithm."

MESSAGE user "What is the difference between a certificate and a certificate signing request?"
MESSAGE assistant "A CSR (Certificate Signing Request) is a request TO a CA asking for a certificate — it contains your public key, domain name, and organization info, signed with your private key. A certificate is what the CA sends back after validating and signing your CSR with their private key. Think of it as: CSR = job application, Certificate = job offer letter. SSLVault generates CSRs automatically when you request certificates at /buy."

MESSAGE user "Can SSLVault work with hardware security modules (HSMs)?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault currently manages certificates and keys in software-based secure storage (KeyLocker). For enterprise HSM requirements, contact support at /contact. HSM integration is on the enterprise roadmap — HSMs provide FIPS 140-2 validated hardware-based key protection, required for certain regulated industries (finance, healthcare, government). The SSLVault API at /developer allows integration with external key management systems."

MESSAGE user "What is the minimum TLS version I should support?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault recommends: Support TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 only. Disable TLS 1.0 (deprecated per RFC 8996) and TLS 1.1 (deprecated per RFC 8996). SSL 2.0 and SSL 3.0 must be disabled — both have critical vulnerabilities (POODLE, etc.). TLS 1.3 is significantly faster (1-RTT handshake) and more secure. Most clients support TLS 1.2+. Check your current TLS support at /ssl-health-score."

MESSAGE user "What is an ACME challenge?"
MESSAGE assistant "ACME challenges are how a CA verifies you control a domain: DNS-01 Challenge: Create a TXT record at _acme-challenge.yourdomain.com. SSLVault uses this — the agent automates it via your DNS provider API. HTTP-01 Challenge: Place a specific file at yourdomain.com/.well-known/acme-challenge/. Requires HTTP access to your server. TLS-ALPN-01 Challenge: Serve a specific certificate on port 443. SSLVault primarily uses DNS-01 as it works with wildcards and doesn't require web server changes."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up Dynadot DNS in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Dynadot: 1) Log into Dynadot → My Account → API → Generate API key. 2) Copy the API key. 3) In SSLVault at /dns-providers, select Dynadot and enter your API key. 4) Ensure your domain's nameservers are set to Dynadot's nameservers. Dynadot supports TXT record automation needed for DNS challenge validation."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate transparency poisoning?"
MESSAGE assistant "CT log poisoning refers to attempts to flood CT logs with fraudulent or meaningless certificates to make genuine certificates harder to find. The CT ecosystem has protections against this. SSLVault's CT Monitor at /ct-monitor specifically watches for unusual certificate issuance patterns for your domains, filtering noise and alerting on genuine new certificates. If you see unexpected certificates for your domain, investigate immediately and contact your CA."

MESSAGE user "How does auto-renewal work for wildcard certificates?"
MESSAGE assistant "Wildcard certificates (*.yourdomain.com) require DNS-01 validation — HTTP validation doesn't work for wildcards. SSLVault's auto-renewal: 30 days before expiry, the agent creates a TXT record at _acme-challenge.yourdomain.com via your DNS provider API, GoGetSSL validates it, issues the new wildcard certificate, agent installs it, agent removes the TXT record. Fully automated if DNS credentials are configured."

MESSAGE user "What is the Hover DNS setup in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Hover: Hover's API is limited. SSLVault may support Hover via their unofficial API or manual DNS validation. If Hover isn't listed in /dns-providers, use manual DNS validation: SSLVault will show you the TXT record to add, you add it manually in Hover's DNS management, then click verify in SSLVault. Consider migrating to a provider with full API support for automation (Cloudflare, Namecheap, Porkbun)."

MESSAGE user "How do I check certificate expiry from the command line?"
MESSAGE assistant "Check expiry with: echo | openssl s_client -servername yourdomain.com -connect yourdomain.com:443 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -dates. Or for a local certificate file: openssl x509 -in certificate.pem -noout -enddate. SSLVault also shows expiry dates in /certvault and sends email alerts. The /renewal-calendar shows all expiry dates visually."

MESSAGE user "What is SSLVault's uptime guarantee?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault's uptime and SLA details are in the terms of service at /terms and pricing page at /pricing. The platform is hosted on Vercel (global CDN) and Supabase (managed database) for high availability. For specific SLA requirements for enterprise plans, contact support at /contact."

MESSAGE user "How do I handle expired certificates on my server?"
MESSAGE assistant "If a certificate has expired: 1) Don't panic — go to /certvault in SSLVault. 2) Click 'Renew' on the expired certificate. 3) Ensure your agent is online (/agent-health) and DNS credentials are configured (/dns-providers). 4) The renewal takes 2-5 minutes. 5) If the agent is offline, fix the agent first. 6) For emergency access, you can issue a new certificate for the same domain at /buy. 7) Avoid generating self-signed certificates as a temporary fix — they cause browser warnings."

MESSAGE user "What is SNI (Server Name Indication)?"
MESSAGE assistant "SNI (Server Name Indication) is a TLS extension that allows a server to host multiple SSL certificates on a single IP address. The client includes the hostname it's connecting to in the TLS handshake, so the server knows which certificate to present. Modern browsers and clients all support SNI. This is why you can run multiple HTTPS sites on one server with one IP. SSLVault fully supports SNI-based multi-site configurations."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up SSL on a load balancer?"
MESSAGE assistant "For load balancer SSL: 1) Issue a certificate via SSLVault for your domain. 2) Download the certificate, chain, and private key from /certvault/keylocker. 3) Upload to your load balancer (AWS ALB, Nginx, HAProxy, etc.). 4) Configure SSL termination at the load balancer level. 5) Backend servers can use HTTP internally (SSL termination) or also HTTPS (SSL passthrough or re-encryption). SSLVault can monitor the load balancer's certificate endpoint for expiry."

MESSAGE user "What is the Public Status page?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault's public status page at /status shows real-time operational status of the SSLVault platform including the dashboard, API, agent connectivity, and certificate issuance services. Check this page if you're experiencing issues — it shows any ongoing incidents or maintenance. Bookmark it for quick status checks."

MESSAGE user "How do I create an API key in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to your SSLVault account settings (accessible from the dashboard). Look for the API Keys or Developer section. Click 'Generate New API Key', give it a name and optionally set permissions and expiry. Copy the key immediately — it's shown once. Use this key in the Authorization header for API calls as documented at /developer."

MESSAGE user "What is the SSLVault AgentInstall modal?"
MESSAGE assistant "The AgentInstall modal appears when you click 'Install Agent' from your dashboard or /install page. It provides a pre-configured one-line bash command with your unique server token embedded. Copy this command and run it on your VPS as root. The modal also shows installation progress and troubleshooting tips if the agent doesn't appear in your dashboard within 5 minutes."

MESSAGE user "What are the system requirements for SSLVault agent?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault agent minimum requirements: OS: Linux with systemd (Ubuntu 18.04+, Debian 10+, CentOS 7+, Rocky Linux 8+). RAM: 512MB minimum (agent uses ~50MB). Disk: 1GB free space. Network: Outbound HTTPS (port 443) access to SSLVault servers and DNS provider APIs. Tools: bash, curl, systemd. Root access for installation. The agent is extremely lightweight — it's a bash script running as a service."

MESSAGE user "How do I troubleshoot agent connectivity issues?"
MESSAGE assistant "Agent connectivity troubleshooting: 1) Check service: systemctl status sslvault-agent. 2) View logs: journalctl -u sslvault-agent -n 100. 3) Test outbound connectivity: curl -I https://frthcwkntciaakqsppss.supabase.co. 4) Check firewall rules: ufw status or iptables -L. 5) Verify server token is correct in agent config. 6) Try reinstalling: go to /install and run the install command again. 7) If still failing, contact support at /contact with the log output."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up SSL for a mail server?"
MESSAGE assistant "For mail server SSL: 1) Issue a certificate for your mail domain (e.g., mail.yourdomain.com) at /buy. 2) Configure Postfix: smtpd_tls_cert_file=/path/to/cert.pem, smtpd_tls_key_file=/path/to/key.pem. 3) Configure Dovecot: ssl_cert = </path/to/cert.pem, ssl_key = </path/to/key.pem. 4) Restart services. 5) Test with: openssl s_client -connect mail.yourdomain.com:587 -starttls smtp. SSLVault can monitor mail server certificates at your mail server's hostname."

MESSAGE user "Can I use SSLVault without installing the agent?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, but with limitations. Without the agent: you can still issue certificates at /buy (manual validation), monitor certificates via SSL Discovery using CT logs or direct connect, use the SSL Health Score, Bulk Scanner, CAA Checker, and other tools. However: auto-renewal won't work (you'll renew manually), DNS automation requires the agent for fully automated flow, and real-time server monitoring won't be available. The agent is strongly recommended for production use."

MESSAGE user "What is the difference between certificate reissue and renewal?"
MESSAGE assistant "Renewal: Extends the validity of a certificate with the same key pair and settings. Happens automatically 30 days before expiry. New certificate with same public/private key. Reissue: Generates a completely new certificate with a new key pair. Same domain and settings but new cryptographic material. Use this when: private key is compromised, changing key type (RSA to ECDSA), adding/removing SANs, or changing key size. Both options available in /certvault."

MESSAGE user "How do I view audit logs in SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "Audit logs track all key access events in SSLVault. View them from your dashboard or in the KeyLocker section at /keylocker. Each log entry shows: timestamp, user who accessed the key, IP address, action taken (viewed, copied, etc.), and which certificate's key was accessed. Audit logs are immutable — they cannot be edited or deleted. Export audit logs for compliance reporting from the dashboard."

MESSAGE user "What is the CLM Dashboard?"
MESSAGE assistant "The CLM (Certificate Lifecycle Management) Dashboard at /dashboard is the main control center for SSLVault. After logging in, you see: certificate inventory summary, expiring certificates alerts, agent status overview, recent activity, SSL Discovery tools (CT Logs, DNS Scan, Server Connect), quick access to issue new certificates, and navigation to all SSLVault features. It's your central hub for managing all certificate operations."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up SSL for FTP?"
MESSAGE assistant "For FTPS (FTP with SSL): 1) Issue a certificate for your FTP server's hostname. 2) For vsftpd: ssl_enable=YES, rsa_cert_file=/path/to/cert.pem, rsa_private_key_file=/path/to/key.pem. 3) For ProFTPD: TLSEngine on, TLSRSACertificateFile /path/to/cert.pem, TLSRSACertificateKeyFile /path/to/key.pem. 4) Restart the FTP service. Use FTPS (port 990) or explicit FTPS (port 21 with STARTTLS). Consider switching to SFTP (SSH-based) for simpler security management."

MESSAGE user "Does SSLVault have a mobile app?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault doesn't currently have a dedicated mobile app, but the web dashboard at easysecurity.in is fully responsive and works well on mobile browsers (iOS Safari, Android Chrome). You can monitor certificates, check agent status, and get VaultBrain AI support from your mobile device. A native mobile app may be on the roadmap — check /pricing or contact support at /contact for updates."

MESSAGE user "What is certificate pinning in mobile apps and should I use SSLVault certificates for it?"
MESSAGE assistant "For mobile app certificate pinning with SSLVault-issued certificates: pin the CA's intermediate certificate (not the end-entity certificate) to avoid breaking the app on every renewal. Better approach: pin the public key (SPKI pinning) rather than the full certificate — the public key remains stable across renewals if you use the same key pair. Use certificate renewal (same key) not reissue (new key) to maintain pinned keys. Consider the risks carefully — misconfigured pinning can lock users out of your app."

MESSAGE user "How do I set up SSL for Kubernetes?"
MESSAGE assistant "For Kubernetes SSL with SSLVault: Option 1 (cert-manager style): Use SSLVault API to issue certificates, store as Kubernetes Secrets, mount in Ingress or pods. Option 2 (Ingress): Issue certificate via SSLVault, create TLS Secret: kubectl create secret tls my-cert --cert=cert.pem --key=key.pem, reference in Ingress spec. Option 3 (Agent): Run SSLVault agent on a node, configure to write certs to a shared volume. SSLVault's developer API at /developer supports programmatic certificate management for Kubernetes workflows."

MESSAGE user "What is the SSLVault 47-day readiness feature?"
MESSAGE assistant "SSLVault's 47-Day Readiness feature helps organizations prepare for the upcoming industry change where maximum SSL certificate validity will be reduced to 47 days. The Readiness Dashboard at /readiness shows your compliance status and helps you: verify auto-renewal is properly configured, ensure agent is online and DNS credentials are valid, identify certificates that need configuration updates for shorter lifespans. This proactive readiness check ensures no certificate expiry surprises when the 47-day limit takes effect."

MESSAGE user "What does RFC 8555 mean for SSLVault?"
MESSAGE assistant "RFC 8555 is the IETF standard defining the ACME (Automated Certificate Management Environment) protocol. It standardizes how certificate authorities and subscribers automate certificate issuance and renewal. SSLVault's agent implements ACME-compatible workflows to automate certificate lifecycle operations. Compliance with RFC 8555 ensures SSLVault's automation works reliably with ACME-compatible CAs and that the issuance process follows industry-standard security practices."

